{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4df48118-caed-4f8f-ab53-aca3ce1199d8","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a `dotnet tool` on NuGet.org:\n\n### 1. `.csproj` — Required Properties\n\nAdd these to your `<PropertyGroup>`:\n\n```xml\n<PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n<ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName> <!-- CLI command name -->\n<PackageOutputType>Exe</PackageOutputType>\n<PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n<Version>1.0.0</Version>\n<Authors>YourName</Authors>\n<Description>An MCP server for …</Description>\n<PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n<PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n```\n\n### 2. Pack & Publish\n\n```bash\ndotnet pack -c Release\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_NUGET_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### 3. Users Install & Run\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\n### Key Points\n\n- **`PackAsTool`** is the critical property — it tells `dotnet pack` to produce a tool package instead of a library.\n- **`ToolCommandName`** controls the CLI command name users will type.\n- The project **must** target `Exe` (console app), which your stdio MCP server already is.\n- Get a NuGet API key from [nuget.org/account/apikeys](https://www.nuget.org/account/apikeys).\n- Optionally include a `README.md` via `<None Include=\"README.md\" Pack=\"true\" PackagePath=\"/\" />`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"31b9cc00-7d52-4164-a908-0401bfb1d5e3","outputTokens":482,"requestId":"CC27:1E21:6C3C31D:78B48FA:69EAC1CF"},"id":"a432b486-5b74-43b1-80fb-288974476270","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:05:29.316Z","parentId":"88bfd5d8-0eca-46e3-b6e5-5d24ceedfba1"}
